I walked down Ramp \"B\" and on the 2nd floor, the window was open and i felt the cold air coming inside, For one split second, i thought about just going in the cold, i stopped and turned back around to the third floor to put on some sweatpants. I ended up staying in my warm room and convinced myself that i would go Friday instead. Then early Friday morning like at around 5:30am or so i received a call from a friend in Austin to check if i was ok since i had also told her that I was planning on going that night to help out at the BONFIRE. The celebration, in the Gates Ballroom of the Memorial Student Center, was hosted by the Texas Aggie Corps of Cadets Association as part of the Rally to the Guidons event that weekend.\r\n\r\nOl' Sarge first appeared in October 1938 in a cartoon in the \"Battalion Humor Magazine\" as a character called \"Magarkin,\" drawn by Tumlinson, a freshman artist. Magarkin was later promoted to an upperclassman sergeant who continually harassed another of Tumlinson's creations, \"Fish Blotto.\" Tumlinson would later introduce other popular features, including \"Battalion Betty\" and \"The Tumlinson Boy.\"\r\n\r\nTumlinson died in 2008. His brother, Dick Tumlinson '51, has published a new book of Dick's artistry, using original proof copies of issues of the \"Battalion Humor Magazine\" published from 1938 through 1942. Caleb was a junior University Studies major in the College of Liberal Arts from Sequin and served as the Training Sergeant for Company P-2. He was pursuing a Navy contract. All who knew Caleb remember him as a sociable, confident young man who had a resilient work ethic and a good sense of humor. He was a very well-liked young man, and his loss will affect all of us for a long time to come.\r\n\r\nI want to offer my condolences to Caleb Tate\u2019s family, friends and fellow cadets on his loss. We all stand together as Aggies today as we mourn the loss of one of our own. Caleb Tate will be missed by all of us.\r\n\r\nAs an Aggie, I hope the Tate family will take solace in knowing that Caleb will never be forgotten, and that the unique Aggie spirit of camaraderie that is such an integral part of Texas A&M and the Corps of Cadets will hold fast for them in this very difficult time.\r\n\r\n\u201cWe are the Aggies, the Aggies are we. "before": "MQ=="}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "100000038408685", "name": "Dion Brugger"}, "like_count": 1, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2013-01-23T18:10:04+0000", "message": "Seeking A Few Good Men: Aggie Marine Iraq War Veteran Seeks Fellow Sailor & Marine Veterans For 10 Year Reunion of Historic BattleMarch 23, 2013 is the 10th Anniversary of the Battle of An-Nasiriyah, the first major engagement of United States Marines in the Iraq War. \n\nA small group of veterans of the intense, hard-fought battle are organizing a reunion at the National Museum of the Marine Corps in Quantico, Virginia to commemorate the occasion and they need your help. \"We are looking across the nation for fellow veterans of the Battle of An-Nasiriyah and Task Force Tarawa -  the Marine Corps and Naval Units involved in the battle,\" says Dion Brugger Class of '00, former member of Company C-2, Marine Iraq War Veteran and reunion organizer.  \"If anyone was or knows a Marine who was at Nasiriyah, please have them visit the reunion website at www.tftreunion.org and register for the event, even if they don't know how they\u2019re going to get there yet. We're working on getting sponsors to help with that.\" You can also receive information about the reunion by emailing TFTReunion@gmail.com or by visiting the reunion Facebook Event page and Twitter feed. \n\nOf the 7,100 US Marines and Sailors of Task Force Tarawa, Brugger hopes that between 300 to 500 Marines and Sailors will gather on March 23rd in Quantico, Virginia to commemorate the occasion - together. Reunion attendees can also visit Arlington National Cemetery and buildings on the United States Marine Corps Base at Quantico named in honor of two Marines killed in the battle - 1st Lt. Frederick E. Pokorney, Jr and Gunnery Sergeant Phillip A. Jordan. They will meet authors who wrote books on the battle and share artifacts, photographs, and memories.\n\nOrganizers are also seeking sponsors for the event to offset the costs born by the Iraq War Veterans attending the reunion. Sponsor dollars will go to pay for the evening social at the Museum, bus transportation, and even to help offset the travel costs of those veterans who could otherwise not afford to travel to the reunion. \n\nTo help support the reunion, please visit the reunion website at www.tftreunion.org or contact Mr. Brugger by emailTFTReunion@gmail.com.\n\nDion Brugger graduated from Texas A&M in May of 2000 and was commissioned a Marine Officer. After attending The Basic School in Quantico Virginia, he attended Field Artillery School in Ft. Sill, Oklahoma. His first duty station was Camp Lejeune, NC, where he checked in to 1st Battalion 10th Marines on July 1st, 2001. Ironically, his Battalion Commanding Officer Lt Col. Glen Starnes, was also a Aggie, class of '85 and also a former member of company C-2. \n\nDion participated in numerous training exercises all over the globe until the 2nd Marine Division was called to duty while on new years leave January 3rd, 2003. By Jan 15th, 2003 the 2nd Marine Expeditionary Brigade, to become known as \"Task Force Tarawa\" had boarded seven ships and sailing to the Persian Gulf.\n\nThe rest of Task Force Tarawa's story is provided in some of news articles collected on our reunion website...http://www.tftreunion.org/Our_History_in_the_News.php . At least seven books have been written about the Battle of An Nasiriyah and the Marines of Task Force Tarawa.\n\n-Semper Fi-\nDion Brugger '00 Company C-2", "id": "531148663584320_93280985", "user_likes": false}]}, "message": "Howdy, Ags!
